<div class="courseblock main">
<p class="courseblocktitle"><strong>ARCH&#160;26005.  Cities by Design.  100 Units.</strong></p><p class="courseblockdesc">
This course examines the theory and practice of city design-how, throughout history, people have sought to mold and shape cities in pre-determined ways. The form of the city is the result of myriad factors, but in this course we will hone in on the purposeful act of designing cities according to normative thinking-ideas about how cities ought to be. Using examples from all time periods and places around the globe, we will examine how cities are purposefully designed and what impact those designs have had. Where and when has city design been successful, and where has it resulted in more harm than good?</p><p class="courseblockdetail">
Instructor(s): Evan Carver&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Terms Offered: Winter<br />
Equivalent Course(s): GEOG 26005, PBPL 26005, ENST 26005<br />
</p>
